<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900518-0030</DOCNO><DOCID>900518-0030.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   World-Wide</HL><DATE>05/18/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   GORBACHEV MET with Lithuania's premier to discussVilnius's secession bid.   In what was considered a major breakthrough in atwo-month-old confrontation over the Baltic republic'sproclamation of independence, the Soviet leader held twohours of talks in the Kremlin with Lithuania's Prime MinisterPrunskiene, who traveled to Moscow with an offer of newconcessions. The official Tass news agency reported thatGorbachev reaffirmed that the republic must rescind itsdeclaration, saying Lithuania's proposal to suspend itssecession drive and remain part of the Soviet security systemdidn't address the issue.</LP><TEXT>   Secretary of State Baker, reportedly deadlocked inarms-control talks in Moscow with Shevardnadze, said he wouldmeet today with Prunskiene to discuss the situation in thebreakaway state.   ---   Bush and West Germany's Kohl held talks in Washington onGerman unification and other East-West issues. The president,preparing for this month's superpower summit, expressedsupport for a united Germany with &quot;full control over all itsterritory,&quot; and said reunification should end the allies'postwar rights in Germany.   ---   The Pentagon announced that the U.S. isn't asking NATOallies to increase defense budgets by 3% a year, a reversalof longstanding policy. The decision, which was to beunveiled at a meeting of defense ministers next week, cameamid an extensive review by the alliance of its militaryneeds amid the political changes in East Europe.   ---   Bush said that while he won't tolerate discrimination inhiring, he would reject any legislation that imposes quotason employers. Following the president's White House comments,congressional Democrats and Republicans unveiled a compromiseamendment to an anti-bias measure that is intended to dealwith Bush's objections.   ---   About 150,000 state employees returned to work inNicaragua, ending a weeklong strike that crippled services inManagua and strained the nation's already troubled economy.As part of the settlement, President Chamorro's governmentagreed to double the salaries of the public workers.   ---   The Dominican Republic's Bosch accused conservativePresident Balaguer of fraud in Wednesday's presidentialelection, and he called for street demonstrations. Partialreturns from the nationwide balloting showed the leftistformer president, who was toppled in a 1963 coup, trailingBalaguer.   ---   A jury in Brooklyn convicted a white teen-ager ofsecond-degree murder in the racial slaying of 16-year-oldblack Yusuf Hawkins in August 1989. Joseph Fama, 19, accusedof being the triggerman in the killing in the New York Cityborough, faces 25 years to life in prison. A second jury isdeliberating the case against a co-defendant.   ---   Romanian politicians concluded campaigning for Sunday'spresidential and parliamentary balloting, the country's firstfree elections in 53 years. While about 70,000 backers ofinterim President Iliescu rallied in Bucharest, tens ofthousands of demonstrators branded him a &quot;neo-Communist.&quot;   ---   The republic of Slovenia appeared headed for a clash withYugoslavia's federal authorities, saying it would resist anyemergency measures to restrict its autonomy. Belgrade'seight-member presidency announced Wednesday that it wouldtake &quot;urgent steps&quot; to prevent separatist moves.   ---   A special London investigator said some members of theBritish army have passed intelligence documents to loyalistProtestant terrorists in Northern Ireland. The datareportedly was about Irish Republic Army members. Theofficial said 94 people had been arrested as a result of theinquiry.   ---   Police in South Korea fought stone-throwing students inKwangju and a dozen other cities, part of nationwide protestscalled by a dissident coalition to mark today's 10thanniversary of a crushed anti-government rebellion in thesouthern city. In Ulsan, 27,000 workers at the nation'slargest car plant continued a strike for a third day.   ---   Negotiators in Manila attempted to break a deadlock overthe future of U.S. military bases in the Philippines, failingto resolve a dispute over whether Washington has made fullpayments for the installations. The round of talks isscheduled to end today.   ---   Israel's President Herzog granted Prime Minister Shamir a21-day extension on his mandate to form a new government.Shamir had cited disputes with potential partners over thedistribution of cabinet posts. The country's Labor-Likudcoalition collapsed March 15 over Shamir's refusal to acceptU.S. proposals for Israeli-Palestinian talks.   ---   South African police guarded a gold mine in Welkom, about180 miles south of Johannesburg, after two whites were killedWednesday in a clash with black workers. In Brussels,President de Klerk, who is on a nine-nation tour, said hewouldn't let extremists of any type interfere with his plansto ease South Africa's apartheid system.</TEXT></DOC>